# Vercel Web Analytics Implementation

## Summary
Successfully implemented Vercel Web Analytics for the Research Advisor Frontend project.

## Changes Made

### 1. Installed Dependencies
- Added `@vercel/analytics` package (version 1.6.1) to the project using npm
- Updated `package.json` and `package-lock.json` accordingly

### 2. Modified Files
- **src/App.tsx**: Added Vercel Analytics tracking component

### Implementation Details

#### src/App.tsx
- Added import statement: `import { Analytics } from '@vercel/analytics/react'`
- Integrated the `<Analytics />` component in all three main views of the application:
  1. Landing view (line 214)
  2. Results view (line 240)
  3. Chat view (line 287)

This ensures that analytics tracking is active across all user interactions within the application, providing comprehensive visitor and page view tracking.

## Framework Context
This is a React + Vite + TypeScript project, so I followed the Create React App pattern from the Vercel Web Analytics documentation, using the React-specific import path (`@vercel/analytics/react`).

## Build Verification
- Successfully ran `npm run build` to verify the TypeScript compilation and production build work correctly
- Build completed without errors, generating optimized production assets

## Next Steps for Deployment
Once deployed to Vercel:
1. Enable Web Analytics in the Vercel dashboard (Analytics tab for this project)
2. After deployment, verify the `/_vercel/insights/view` endpoint is accessible in the browser's Network tab
3. View analytics data in the Vercel dashboard after users visit the site

## Technical Notes
- The Analytics component is lightweight and doesn't require additional configuration
- It automatically tracks page views and visitor metrics
- Route support is built-in for React applications
- No breaking changes were introduced to existing functionality
